## Proposed Architecture

### System Model (Coordinator-Worker)

The distributed prime-finding app (Task 4) will likely use a **coordinator-worker** pattern:

```
┌─────────────┐       ┌──────────┐
│ Coordinator │──────▶│ Worker 1 │
│             │──────▶│ Worker 2 │
│             │──────▶│ Worker 3 │
└──────┬──────┘       └──────────┘
       │
       ▼
  ┌──────────┐
  │  DFS     │  (fs/replication/)
  │  Servers │
  └──────────┘
```

> [!TIP]
> **Topology Independence:** The Chandy-Lamport algorithm natively supports **any network topology** (ring, mesh, peer-to-peer). 
> 
> By designing the `SnapshotManager` abstractly, any node in the system can initiate a snapshot. The protocol relies only on "incoming channels" and "outgoing channels" between generic peers. 
> 
> Even if Task 4 decides to use a purely peer-to-peer topology without a central coordinator, the `SnapshotManager` will seamlessly adapt: every node simply writes its own local state shard to the DFS, or one node aggregates them.

### What Gets Snapshotted

The Chandy-Lamport algorithm captures a **consistent global snapshot** without stopping computation:

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant C as Coordinator (Initiator)
    participant W1 as Worker 1
    participant W2 as Worker 2

    Note over C: Periodic timer fires → initiate snapshot
    C->>C: Record own local state
    C->>W1: MARKER message
    C->>W2: MARKER message

    Note over W1: First MARKER received
    W1->>W1: Record own local state
    W1->>C: MARKER (back)
    W1->>W2: MARKER (forward)
    Note over W1: Start recording msgs from C until MARKER from C arrives (already got it → channel empty)

    Note over W2: First MARKER received
    W2->>W2: Record own local state
    W2->>C: MARKER (back)
    W2->>W1: MARKER (forward)

    Note over C: Received MARKERs from all → snapshot complete
    C->>C: Save snapshot to DFS
```

### What Gets Snapshotted

Each process (coordinator + workers) records its **local state** when it sees the first MARKER:

| Process | Local State to Capture |
|---|---|
| **Coordinator** | Which files have been assigned, to whom; which chunks are done; current contents of `primes.txt` (found primes so far); worker list |
| **Worker** | Which file/chunk it's currently processing; its progress offset within the chunk; primes found locally (not yet reported) |

**Channel state**: Messages in transit between processes at snapshot time. In our system, these are primarily "result" messages (worker → coordinator) and "assignment" messages (coordinator → worker). The Chandy-Lamport algorithm captures these by recording messages received between the local state save and the MARKER arrival on each channel.

### Snapshot Storage

The snapshot is serialized (JSON/pickle) and stored in the DFS as a file:
- `snapshot_<timestamp>.json` — contains the full global state
- Written via the existing `ReplicatedAFSClientStub.create()` / `open()` / `write()` / `close()` API

